		<subsection xml:id="the-data">
			<title>The Data</title>

			<p>
				Between 1967 and 1977 there was a moratorium on the death penalty in the U.S. A main reason for this was the belief that there was racial bias in the application of the death penalty. When the racial bias argument was tested in court, defenders of the death penalty produced a contingency table for black and white defendants convicted of a capital crime in one state.
			</p>

			<p>
				The code below recreates the dataset documenting the outcome of 326 capital convictions, the race of the defendant, and the race of the victim. Don’t worry too much about this code.
			</p>

			<pre>penalty &lt;- c(rep(1,30), rep(0,184), rep(1,6), rep(0,106))
penalty &lt;- factor(penalty, levels = c(1, 0), labels = c("Death", "Not"))
victim_race &lt;- c(rep(0,214), rep(1,112))
victim_race &lt;- factor(victim_race, levels = c(1, 0), labels = c("Black", "White"))
defendant_race &lt;- c(rep(1,11), rep(0,19), rep(1,52), rep(0,132), rep(1,6), rep(1,97),rep(0,9))
defendant_race &lt;- factor(defendant_race, levels = c(1, 0), labels = c("Black", "White"))
DPenalty &lt;- data.frame(penalty, defendant_race, victim_race)</pre>

			<p>
				What follows is a fully-worked example of inference for independence of two categorical variables. After this first example you will complete a related inference test following the rubric of inference.
			</p>

		</subsection>

		<subsection xml:id="research-question">
			<title>Research question</title>

			<p>
				Is there a relationship between the race of the defendant and whether or not the defendant received the death penalty or are race of the defendent and the application of the death penalty independent?
			</p>

		</subsection>

