			<subsubsection xml:id="identify-the-sample-or-samples-and-a-reasonable-population-or-populations-of-interest.">
				<title>Identify the sample (or samples) and a reasonable population (or populations) of interest.</title>

				<p>
					The sample consists of 326 captial convictions drawn from one state. The population of interest is presumably all captial convictions.
				</p>

			</subsubsection>

			<subsubsection xml:id="express-the-null-and-alternative-hypotheses-as-contextually-meaningful-full-sentences.">
				<title>Express the null and alternative hypotheses as contextually meaningful full sentences.</title>

				<p>
					<em>H</em>0: Defendant race and death penalty conviction are independent.
				</p>

				<p>
					<em>H</em><em>A</em>: Defendant race and death penalty conviction are dependent.
				</p>

			</subsubsection>

			<subsubsection xml:id="express-the-null-and-alternative-hypotheses-in-symbols-when-possible.">
				<title>Express the null and alternative hypotheses in symbols (when possible).</title>

				<p>
					The Chi-square test for independence does not have a convenient symbolic description.
				</p>

			</subsubsection>
		</subsection>

		<subsection xml:id="model">
			<title>Model</title>


			<subsubsection xml:id="identify-the-sampling-distribution-model.">
				<title>Identify the sampling distribution model.</title>

				<p>
					We will use a Chi-square model with 1 degree of freedom.
				</p>

			</subsubsection>

			<subsubsection xml:id="check-the-relevant-conditions-to-ensure-that-model-assumptions-are-met.">
				<title>Check the relevant conditions to ensure that model assumptions are met.</title>

				<p><ul>
					<li>
					Random

				<p><ul>
					<li>
					Since the 326 individuals in the sample are all capital convictions from one state we do not have a random sample but we hope they are representative of all capital cases.
					</li>

				</ul></p>
					</li>

					<li>
					10%

				<p><ul>
					<li>
					326 patients are less than 10% of all capital convitions.
					</li>

				</ul></p>
					</li>

					<li>
					Expected cell counts

				<p><ul>
					<li>
					The contingency table above shows the expected counts. We can verify that they are all greater than 5.
					</li>

				</ul></p>
					</li>

				</ul></p>

			</subsubsection>
		</subsection>

		<subsection xml:id="mechanics">
			<title>Mechanics</title>


			<subsubsection xml:id="compute-the-test-statistic.">
				<title>Compute the test statistic.</title>

				<pre>defendant_penalty_test &lt;- chisq.test(defendant_penalty_table)
defendant_penalty_test</pre>

				<pre>## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  defendant_penalty_table
## X-squared = 0.086343, df = 1, p-value = 0.7689</pre>

				<p>
					The expected cell counts can be found which will be needed to confirm conditions.
				</p>

				<pre>defendant_penalty_test$expected</pre>

				<pre>##        defendant_race
## penalty     Black     White
##   Death  18.33129  17.66871
##   Not   147.66871 142.33129</pre>

				<p>
					The <c>tidy</c> version of the Chi-Square test helps us identify the degrees of freedom parameter and the test statistic.
				</p>

				<pre>defendant_penalty_test_tidy &lt;- tidy(defendant_penalty_test)
defendant_penalty_test_tidy</pre>

				<pre>## # A tibble: 1 × 4
##   statistic p.value parameter method                                            
##       &lt;dbl&gt;   &lt;dbl&gt;     &lt;int&gt; &lt;chr&gt;                                             
## 1    0.0863   0.769         1 Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity…</pre>

				<p>
					The degrees of freedom is 1 and the Chi-Square test statistic value is 0.0863431.
				</p>

			</subsubsection>

			<subsubsection xml:id="plot-the-null-distribution.">
				<title>Plot the null distribution.</title>

				<pre>pdist("chisq", df = defendant_penalty_test_tidy$parameter,
      q = defendant_penalty_test_tidy$statistic,
      invisible = TRUE)</pre>

				<figure>
	<image source="Death_penalty_and_race_files/figure-markdown_github/unnamed-chunk-10-1.png"/>
					<caption></caption>
</figure>

			</subsubsection>

			<subsubsection xml:id="calculate-the-p-value.">
				<title>Calculate the P-value.</title>

				<pre>1 - pdist("chisq", df = defendant_penalty_test_tidy$parameter,
          q = defendant_penalty_test_tidy$statistic,
          plot = FALSE)</pre>

				<pre>## X-squared 
## 0.7688787</pre>

				<p>
					Or we can read the p-value off of the tidy output.
				</p>

				<pre>defendant_penalty_test_tidy$p.value</pre>

				<pre>## [1] 0.7688787</pre>

			</subsubsection>
		</subsection>

		<subsection xml:id="conclusion">
			<title>Conclusion</title>


			<subsubsection xml:id="state-the-statistical-conclusion.">
				<title>State the statistical conclusion.</title>

				<p>
					We fail to reject the null hypothesis.
				</p>

			</subsubsection>

			<subsubsection xml:id="state-but-do-not-overstate-a-contextually-meaningful-conclusion.">
				<title>State (but do not overstate) a contextually meaningful conclusion.</title>

				<p>
					There is insufficient evidence that the defendant’s race and death penalty conviction are associated in capital convictions.
				</p>

			</subsubsection>

			<subsubsection xml:id="identify-the-possibility-of-either-a-type-i-or-type-ii-error-and-state-what-making-such-an-error-means-in-the-context-of-the-hypotheses.">
				<title>Identify the possibility of either a Type I or Type II error and state what making such an error means in the context of the hypotheses.</title>

				<p>
					It’s possible that we have made a Type II error. It may be that defendant race and death penalty convictions are associated, but our sample has not given enough evidence of such an association.
				</p>

			</subsubsection>
		</subsection>

